Universality 
In this section we demonstrate the universality of
the asymptotic polynomials and
their Cauchy transform in the microscopic limit, which then
translates to all correlation functions
of characteristic polynomials through eq. ().
The limit is called microscopic since it includes a certain rescaling of the
eigenvalues with an appropriate power of the parameter ,
according to the spectral region we investigate.
We will first study the microscopic limit at the origin (frequently
called the "hard edge"). This case is singled out due to the presence of
logarithms in the potential.
The correlations in the bulk of the spectrum then follow easily.
Furthermore we also study the edge of
the spectrum defined by the endpoints of the support of the macroscopic or
smoothed spectral density at large  ("soft edge").
Here we will restrict ourselves to the cases
where the spectrum support is a simply connected
interval, the so-called one-cut phase. We will also stay away
from multicritical points, where the macroscopic density develops extra
zeros at the boundary of spectra or inside the support.
This amounts to requiring the limiting functions for  to be
nonvanishing on the support as well (see eq. () below).
While such multicritical
cases can be, in principle, analyzed in the framework of the same approach
 the issue becomes much more subtle
due to subleading terms in the large- expansion.

Our first step is to derive the large- limit of the differential equations
() and (). Our assumption of the one-cut support
is equivalent to the fact
that in the large- limit the recursion
coefficients  in eq. () approach a single valued function
_n c_n=c(t=n/N) .
While in the earlier physical matrix model literature
this assumption was introduced as an ansatz supported by numerical evidence,
it has been proved rigorously in the recent mathematical literature
.
Eq. () implies the following asymptotic form
for the functions  and  in the differential
equation:
