Let us now justify our choice of the type of Bessel functions
featuring in eq. ().
Due to the singularity at the origin we have to choose
between Bessel functions of second kind (also known as Weber
functions), ,
and the Hankel functions. We give two independent arguments in favor of
the latter choice.
The first reason for selecting the Hankel functions is that it allows
one to match the known "bulk" asymptotic result after
taking the asymptotic limit .
While the Weber functions would asymptotically produce sine
and cosine terms (as the Bessel functions of first kind do), the
Cauchy transforms in the bulk were shown to
approach .
This asymptotic is correctly reproduced by the Hankel functions.
The second argument is related with the necessity to distinguish between
the two types of the Hankel functions  and
 according to the sign of .




In fact, for  and Gaussian potential 
one can explicitly write down the integral representations
for the polynomials and Cauchy transforms at finite-, as discussed
in.
